What I say to my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I often travel abroad, and my foreign friends always ask with varying degrees of perplexity: but what is going on in your country?
Here is what I respond to them.
Firstly, be careful not to misunderstand the 2016 elections.
Contrary to certain comments, the American political system has not been swept away by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elites.
Donald Trump capitalized on the trend associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
And yet, Trump fell short of winning the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the elections by tapping into populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand more votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the Electoral College and the presidency.
Nevertheless, Trump's victory highlights the real issue of increasing social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The last bestseller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the big difference between California and the Appalachians.
The research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income White Americans without college degrees are worse than those of African-Americans, who historically have been at the bottom of inequality.
In 1999, the mortality rates among whites without college education were around 30% lower than those of African Americans; in 2015, they were 30% higher.
Moreover, employment in industry, which was once one of the main sources of well-paid jobs for white working-class people, has sharply declined over the last generation, comprising only 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were seduced by Trump's promises to shake things up and bring jobs back to the industry.
Ironically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's health care legislation are likely to make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that you must not underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his rages on Twitter and his scandalous contempt for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is to monopolize the viewers' attention, and that the best way to do this is to make extreme statements without worrying about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother its supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his permanent self-centered campaign mode to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that discourages some allies whom he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who fails to win the popular vote moves toward the political center to attract more support.
This is what George W. Bush achieved successfully in 2001.
On the contrary, Trump claims that he won the popular vote and acts as if it were truly the case, which pleases his base of supporters.
Although Trump made solid centrist picks for the Department of Defense, State, and National Security, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services sit at the extremes of the Republican Party.
The staff at the White House is divided between ideologues and pragmatists - and it intends to satisfy both camps at once.
Fourthly, one must not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling and ask me if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
The United States, despite its many problems, is not Italy in 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as divided.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' objective was not to ensure that the government was harmonious, but to limit political power through a system of checks and balances that makes it difficult to exercise this power.
The joke goes that the founders set up a political system such that it is impossible for King George to rule over us — impossible for him or anyone else.
The inefficiency has been put to the service of freedom.
The presidency of Trump is still in its early stages and we cannot be certain of what might happen afterward, say, in the wake of a major terrorist attack.
However, until now, the courts, the Congress, and the states have overseen this balance of powers within the administration, as Madison wished.
And the permanent executive service officials still carry weight.
Finally, my friends wonder what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Honestly, I don't know, but I'm less concerned about China's rise than about Trump's.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free-riders, the United States has long been a frontrunner in providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the international order under US leadership facing various problems, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can affirm with certainty that it will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major party candidate in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since his inauguration in January, Trump's statements and those of his allies suggest that he is likely to persist.
The power to coerce and the power to persuade of the United States, after all, come largely from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help to manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is more uncertain.
The translation of the given French sentence to English is:  "The director of Trump's budget speaks of a constraining power budget, with cuts made to the State Department and the United Nations system."
Here is the translation of the given French sentence into English:  "Other government members argue for replacing multilateral trade agreements with 'fair and balanced' bilateral arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change."
I tell my friends that I would like to be able to reassure them about these issues.
But I cannot.
